               <p>1759. <persName id="def1-1759-18460817" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1759-18460817" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1759-18460817" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1759-18460817" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1759-18460817" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JAMES SMITH</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18460817-1759-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18460817-1759-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18460817-1759-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp> for that <persName id="t18460817-name-1463">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1463" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1463" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1463" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>Henry Harland, the younger</persName>, being in the dwelling-bouse of <persName id="t18460817-name-1464" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1464" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1464" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1464" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460817-1759-offence-1 t18460817-name-1464"></join>John Harland</persName>, did steal 1 watch, value 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; and 1 coat, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18460817-name-1465" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1465" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1465" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1465" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460817-1759-offence-1 t18460817-name-1465"></join>Richard Harland</persName>: 1 mantle, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 1 shawl, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18460817-name-1466" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1466" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1466" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1466" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460817-1759-offence-1 t18460817-name-1466"></join>John Harland</persName>: 1 waistcoat, 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 belt, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 3 scarfs, 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 shawl, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 3 shirt-collars, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.: and having committed the said felony, did feloniously and burglariously break out of the same dwelling-house: that the prisoner did incite him the felony aforesaid to do and commit, and felo<lb></lb>niously received the same goods, well knowing them to have been stolen.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RYLAHD</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1467" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1467" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1467" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1467" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD HARLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. My father's name is John Harland—I have a brother named John, and another named Henry—we all live with my father, in Union-row, Old Kent-road. My brother Henry went to bed on the night of the 5th of July—in the morning I was awoke, and he was gone—he had slept in the same bed with me—I missed a watch and a coat—I took a deal of pains to find Henry—I saw him again about ten days after, about the Wednesday week—he was then in custody—the policeman produced the articles to me which I had missed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you go to bed that night? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Between eleven and twelve o'clock—all was then shut up safe—our house is in the parish of St. Mary, Newington—the watch was worth 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and the cost 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—there were other things gone belonging to my father and mother, to the amount of 7<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. or 8<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1468" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1468" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1468" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1468" type="given" value="PRISCILLA"></interp>PRISCILLA HARLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Harland. On the morning of the 6th of July I missed a great-coat of my husband's, a mantle and shawl of my own, and various articles belonging to my son John.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1469" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1469" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1469" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1469" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HARLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a son of the last witness. On the morning of the 6th of July I missed three coats, four or five pairs of trowsers, five waistcoats, and some other things—I saw a handkerchief produced by Kerney—I had not missed it, but I afterwards found I had missed such a thing—I went down to Brighton, and I saw my brother's watch and a coat at Mr. Lewis's, the pawnbroker—I shut up our house safely on Sunday night, the 5th of July, about half-past eleven o'clock.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184608170239"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1470" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1470" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1470" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1470" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HARLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am fourteen years old. On the night of Sunday, the 5th of July, I went to bed with my brother in my father's house—I went away at four o'clock the next morning—I had been living with Nosworthy and Wells, in Coleman-street, for about seven months—I found the prisoner there—when I had been there about six weeks, he asked whether I had got a pair of trowsers I could let him have—I told him no—he still kept asking me and bothering me, and I took a pair of my own trowsers from home, and sold them to him—he said he would give me 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for them, but he did not—he gave me 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—some time after he asked me for another pair—he said these were almost worn out, he wanted a pair for Sunday—I took a pair of my brother's, and sold them to him for 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he paid me for them—these tort of things went on several times—I took various articles—I gave him some and kept some—some nights before I left home I saw the prisoner—I bad a sove<lb></lb>reign of my master's, and he was afraid I should confess—he advised me to divide the sovereign with him—he said it would be better for me to come away from home, for if Mr. Nosworthy found out about the sovereign, I should be transported—he advised me to go away, and go to sea—he told me to get plenty of things, and plenty of money, and he would try and dispose of the things, and give me some of the money, and keep half of it—it was in consequence of that I took all these things on the Sunday night and ran away—I went to the prisoner's lodging at half-past five in the morning—I found him getting up when I got there—I had got ail these things with me—I gave him some of the oldest things—he went out to work, and alter that hit wife pawned a coat for 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the prisoner came home, and said there was a piece of work, a policeman was after me, and I had better be off—he advised me to go to Brighton—I carried some of the things away with me—I took the watch and a coat of my brother's—I went to Brighton—I pawned the watch and coat in Ship-street, Brighton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean to swear that the prisoner excited you to do all these things? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, it was in consequence of his advice I did it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1471" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1471" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1471" type="surname" value="KERNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1471" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES KERNEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant P</hi> 36.) I heard of this robbery, and on, the 11 tb of July I went to the prisoner's lodgings—I told him to be particular in what he said, for I was sure if Harland was not there he knew where he was—He said, "I know nothing about him, I have not seen him for six week"—I found on Henry Harland this powder-flask—he said the prisoner gave it him—the prisoner said he knew nothing about the powder-flask, be never had such a thing in his possession—I told him I would take him into custody on suspicion of receiving this property—he said he knew nothing about it—he told me he gave his wife a coat to pawn, which was pawned at Mr. Telford's for 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I went there and found this coat—it is the one that John Harland has identified.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1472" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1472" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1472" type="surname" value="HARLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1472" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HARLAND</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> This is my coat, it is one of the things my brother went off with that morning.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460817-name-1473" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1473" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1473" type="surname" value="ROBINSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460817-name-1473" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN ROBINSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I lived with the prisoner as his wife—I pawned this coat—Henry Harland came and said he had got no money—that his father and mother sent him out to go to sea—he gave me the coat to pawn—I gave him the money and the duplicate—he came twice to our house—he wid he would ask his mother for some old clothes, and I believed it—I took the scarf and the cloak for myself, and said I was very much obliged to him"—I have seen this powder-flask—it belonged to my husband—he gave it to Henry Harland for the sake of his giving me the scarf and cloak.</p>
